        <b><span id="titleLabel">1.2 - The inner game: What goes into the industry's best-selling titles</span></b>
        <table border="1" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="dateTimeLabel">Wednesday, May 10, 11:30 AM - 1:00 PM</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="roomLabel">Room 404AB</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="tableCell" colspan="2"><span id="descriptionLabel">What are the critical elements that drive a game to the top of the sales charts? Is it a recognizable IP? Great gameplay? Innovative features? Technology bells and whistles? A perfectly paced learning curve? Some games that seemed to "have it all" and were released to high scores from reviewers bombed on the sales charts. On the other hand, some games that missed their marks and received dismal ratings have turned out to be blockbuster chart movers. How can those facts be explained? What can be more important than exceptional gameplay and a great feature set? This session will focus on the real-world factors that influence sales. How do recognizable IPs help capture a wider audience? How important is balanced gameplay that challenges core gamers as well as entertains the mass market? What learning curve is the perfect learning curve? How much outside talent is necessary, and how do you manage it appropriately? Accomplished designers discuss how they prioritized these criteria, why they decided to include some and not others, and how their decision s affected sales.</span></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td width="18%" class="tableCell">Moderator:</td>
                <td class="tableCell"><span id="moderatorLabel">Eric Zimmerman, Co-Founder and CEO - gamelab</span></td>
            </tr>
